@chapter Introduction
@c man begin DESCRIPTION 

FFprobe is a very simple and portable prober using the FFmpeg
libraries to probe the content of a file. 

It may be used to print informations about the format and header of a
multimedia file or stream, the multimedia streams and each single
packet or frame.

FFprobe output consists in stanza of the form:
@example
[TAG]
key1=val1
...
keyN=valN
[/TAG]
@end example

and is designed in order to be easily parsable by a textual filter.

FFprobe may be used both as a standalone application or in combination with
a textual filter, which is supposed to perform more sophisticated
elaboration (e.g. statistics elaboration or plotting).
@c man end

@chapter Invocation

@section Syntax
@example
@c man begin SYNOPSIS
ffprobe [options] @file{input_files}
@c man end
@end example

@c man begin OPTIONS
@section Main options

@table @option
@item -h
show help and exit
@item -version
show version and exit
@item -L
show license and exit
@item -pretty
will show every single value using an adequate unit of measure and
using more eye-ball parsable prefixes.
@item -k
keep going even in case of error, always returns 0
@item -read_packets       
read packets info
@item -read_frames
read frames info
@item -show_files
show file info, that is the informations relative to the container
@item -show_frames
show frames info, implies the option -read_frames and -read_packets
@item -show_files
show files info, implies the option -read_packets
@item -show_streams
show streams info, that is the informations relative to the monomedia
streams contained in the header 
@item -show_tags
show tags info: actually are supported only the track, title, author, copyright,
comment, album, year, and genre tags.

@end table
@c man end

